2851/**
2852 * cgroup_apply_control_enable - enable or show csses according to control
2853 * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
2854 *
2855 * Walk @cgrp's subtree and create new csses or make the existing ones
2856 * visible. A css is created invisible if it's being implicitly enabled
2857 * through dependency. An invisible css is made visible when the userland
2858 * explicitly enables it.
2859 *
2860 * Returns 0 on success, -errno on failure. On failure, csses which have
2861 * been processed already aren't cleaned up. The caller is responsible for
2862 * cleaning up with cgroup_apply_control_disable().
2863 */
2864static int cgroup_apply_control_enable(struct cgroup *cgrp)
2865{
2866 struct cgroup *dsct;
2867 struct cgroup_subsys_state *d_css;
2868 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
2869 int ssid, ret;
2870
2871 cgroup_for_each_live_descendant_pre(dsct, d_css, cgrp) {
2872 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
2873 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css = cgroup_css(dsct, ss);
2874
2875 WARN_ON_ONCE(css && percpu_ref_is_dying(&css->refcnt));
2876
2877 if (!(cgroup_ss_mask(dsct) & (1 << ss->id)))
2878 continue;
2879
2880 if (!css) {
2881 css = css_create(dsct, ss);
2882 if (IS_ERR(css))
2883 return PTR_ERR(css);
2884 }
2885
2886 if (css_visible(css)) {
2887 ret = css_populate_dir(css);
2888 if (ret)
2889 return ret;
2890 }
2891 }
2892 }
2893
2894 return 0;
2895}
2896
2897/**
2898 * cgroup_apply_control_disable - kill or hide csses according to control
2899 * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
2900 *
2901 * Walk @cgrp's subtree and kill and hide csses so that they match
2902 * cgroup_ss_mask() and cgroup_visible_mask().
2903 *
2904 * A css is hidden when the userland requests it to be disabled while other
2905 * subsystems are still depending on it. The css must not actively control
2906 * resources and be in the vanilla state if it's made visible again later.
2907 * Controllers which may be depended upon should provide ->css_reset() for
2908 * this purpose.
2909 */
2910static void cgroup_apply_control_disable(struct cgroup *cgrp)
2911{
2912 struct cgroup *dsct;
2913 struct cgroup_subsys_state *d_css;
2914 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
2915 int ssid;
2916
2917 cgroup_for_each_live_descendant_post(dsct, d_css, cgrp) {
2918 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
2919 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css = cgroup_css(dsct, ss);
2920
2921 WARN_ON_ONCE(css && percpu_ref_is_dying(&css->refcnt));
2922
2923 if (!css)
2924 continue;
2925
2926 if (css->parent &&
2927 !(cgroup_ss_mask(dsct) & (1 << ss->id))) {
2928 kill_css(css);
2929 } else if (!css_visible(css)) {
2930 css_clear_dir(css);
2931 if (ss->css_reset)
2932 ss->css_reset(css);
2933 }
2934 }
2935 }
2936}
2937
2938/**
2939 * cgroup_apply_control - apply control mask updates to the subtree
2940 * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
2941 *
2942 * subsystems can be enabled and disabled in a subtree using the following
2943 * steps.
2944 *
2945 * 1. Call cgroup_save_control() to stash the current state.
2946 * 2. Update ->subtree_control masks in the subtree as desired.
2947 * 3. Call cgroup_apply_control() to apply the changes.
2948 * 4. Optionally perform other related operations.
2949 * 5. Call cgroup_finalize_control() to finish up.
2950 *
2951 * This function implements step 3 and propagates the mask changes
2952 * throughout @cgrp's subtree, updates csses accordingly and perform
2953 * process migrations.
2954 */
2955static int cgroup_apply_control(struct cgroup *cgrp)
2956{
2957 int ret;
2958
2959 cgroup_propagate_control(cgrp);
2960
2961 ret = cgroup_apply_control_enable(cgrp);
2962 if (ret)
2963 return ret;
2964
2965 /*
2966 * At this point, cgroup_e_css() results reflect the new csses
2967 * making the following cgroup_update_dfl_csses() properly update
2968 * css associations of all tasks in the subtree.
2969 */
2970 ret = cgroup_update_dfl_csses(cgrp);
2971 if (ret)
2972 return ret;
2973
2974 return 0;
2975}
2976
2977/**
2978 * cgroup_finalize_control - finalize control mask update
2979 * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
2980 * @ret: the result of the update
2981 *
2982 * Finalize control mask update. See cgroup_apply_control() for more info.
2983 */
2984static void cgroup_finalize_control(struct cgroup *cgrp, int ret)
2985{
2986 if (ret) {
2987 cgroup_restore_control(cgrp);
2988 cgroup_propagate_control(cgrp);
2989 }
2990
2991 cgroup_apply_control_disable(cgrp);
2992}
2993
2994static int cgroup_vet_subtree_control_enable(struct cgroup *cgrp, u16 enable)
2995{
2996 u16 domain_enable = enable & ~cgrp_dfl_threaded_ss_mask;
2997
2998 /* if nothing is getting enabled, nothing to worry about */
2999 if (!enable)
3000 return 0;
3001
3002 /* can @cgrp host any resources? */
3003 if (!cgroup_is_valid_domain(cgrp->dom_cgrp))
3004 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3005
3006 /* mixables don't care */
3007 if (cgroup_is_mixable(cgrp))
3008 return 0;
3009
3010 if (domain_enable) {
3011 /* can't enable domain controllers inside a thread subtree */
3012 if (cgroup_is_thread_root(cgrp) || cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
3013 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3014 } else {
3015 /*
3016 * Threaded controllers can handle internal competitions
3017 * and are always allowed inside a (prospective) thread
3018 * subtree.
3019 */
3020 if (cgroup_can_be_thread_root(cgrp) || cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
3021 return 0;
3022 }
3023
3024 /*
3025 * Controllers can't be enabled for a cgroup with tasks to avoid
3026 * child cgroups competing against tasks.
3027 */
3028 if (cgroup_has_tasks(cgrp))
3029 return -EBUSY;
3030
3031 return 0;
3032}

3034/* change the enabled child controllers for a cgroup in the default hierarchy */
3035static ssize_t cgroup_subtree_control_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of,
3036 char *buf, size_t nbytes,
3037 loff_t off)
3038{
3039 u16 enable = 0, disable = 0;
3040 struct cgroup *cgrp, *child;
3041 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
3042 char *tok;
3043 int ssid, ret;
3044
3045 /*
3046 * Parse input - space separated list of subsystem names prefixed
3047 * with either + or -.
3048 */
3049 buf = strstrip(buf);
3050 while ((tok = strsep(&buf, " "))) {
3051 if (tok[0] == '\0')
3052 continue;
3053 do_each_subsys_mask(ss, ssid, ~cgrp_dfl_inhibit_ss_mask) {
3054 if (!cgroup_ssid_enabled(ssid) ||
3055 strcmp(tok + 1, ss->name))
3056 continue;
3057
3058 if (*tok == '+') {
3059 enable |= 1 << ssid;
3060 disable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3061 } else if (*tok == '-') {
3062 disable |= 1 << ssid;
3063 enable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3064 } else {
3065 return -EINVAL;
3066 }
3067 break;
3068 } while_each_subsys_mask();
3069 if (ssid == CGROUP_SUBSYS_COUNT)
3070 return -EINVAL;
3071 }
3072
3073 cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, true);
3074 if (!cgrp)
3075 return -ENODEV;
3076
3077 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
3078 if (enable & (1 << ssid)) {
3079 if (cgrp->subtree_control & (1 << ssid)) {
3080 enable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3081 continue;
3082 }
3083
3084 if (!(cgroup_control(cgrp) & (1 << ssid))) {
3085 ret = -ENOENT;
3086 goto out_unlock;
3087 }
3088 } else if (disable & (1 << ssid)) {
3089 if (!(cgrp->subtree_control & (1 << ssid))) {
3090 disable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3091 continue;
3092 }
3093
3094 /* a child has it enabled? */
3095 cgroup_for_each_live_child(child, cgrp) {
3096 if (child->subtree_control & (1 << ssid)) {
3097 ret = -EBUSY;
3098 goto out_unlock;
3099 }
3100 }
3101 }
3102 }
3103
3104 if (!enable && !disable) {
3105 ret = 0;
3106 goto out_unlock;
3107 }
3108
3109 ret = cgroup_vet_subtree_control_enable(cgrp, enable);
3110 if (ret)
3111 goto out_unlock;
3112
3113 /* save and update control masks and prepare csses */
3114 cgroup_save_control(cgrp);
3115
3116 cgrp->subtree_control |= enable;
3117 cgrp->subtree_control &= ~disable;
3118
3119 ret = cgroup_apply_control(cgrp);
3120 cgroup_finalize_control(cgrp, ret);
3121 if (ret)
3122 goto out_unlock;
3123
3124 kernfs_activate(cgrp->kn);
3125out_unlock:
3126 cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);
3127 return ret ?: nbytes;
3128}

3130/**
3131 * cgroup_enable_threaded - make @cgrp threaded
3132 * @cgrp: the target cgroup
3133 *
3134 * Called when "threaded" is written to the cgroup.type interface file and
3135 * tries to make @cgrp threaded and join the parent's resource domain.
3136 * This function is never called on the root cgroup as cgroup.type doesn't
3137 * exist on it.
3138 */
3139static int cgroup_enable_threaded(struct cgroup *cgrp)
3140{
3141 struct cgroup *parent = cgroup_parent(cgrp);
3142 struct cgroup *dom_cgrp = parent->dom_cgrp;
3143 int ret;
3144
3145 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3146
3147 /* noop if already threaded */
3148 if (cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
3149 return 0;
3150
3151 /*
3152 * If @cgroup is populated or has domain controllers enabled, it
3153 * can't be switched. While the below cgroup_can_be_thread_root()
3154 * test can catch the same conditions, that's only when @parent is
3155 * not mixable, so let's check it explicitly.
3156 */
3157 if (cgroup_is_populated(cgrp) ||
3158 cgrp->subtree_control & ~cgrp_dfl_threaded_ss_mask)
3159 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3160
3161 /* we're joining the parent's domain, ensure its validity */
3162 if (!cgroup_is_valid_domain(dom_cgrp) ||
3163 !cgroup_can_be_thread_root(dom_cgrp))
3164 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3165
3166 /*
3167 * The following shouldn't cause actual migrations and should
3168 * always succeed.
3169 */
3170 cgroup_save_control(cgrp);
3171
3172 cgrp->dom_cgrp = dom_cgrp;
3173 ret = cgroup_apply_control(cgrp);
3174 if (!ret)
3175 parent->nr_threaded_children++;
3176 else
3177 cgrp->dom_cgrp = cgrp;
3178
3179 cgroup_finalize_control(cgrp, ret);
3180 return ret;
3181}

3191 else if (cgroup_is_thread_root(cgrp))

3285 depth = INT_MAX;
3286 } else {
3287 ret = kstrtoint(buf, 0, &depth);
3288 if (ret)
3289 return ret;
3290 }
3291
3292 if (depth < 0)
3293 return -ERANGE;
3294
3295 cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, false);
3296 if (!cgrp)
3297 return -ENOENT;
3298
3299 cgrp->max_depth = depth;
3300
3301 cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);
3302
3303 return nbytes;
3304}

3342static ssize_t cgroup_file_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of, char *buf,
3343 size_t nbytes, loff_t off)
3344{
3345 struct cgroup_namespace *ns = current->nsproxy->cgroup_ns;
3346 struct cgroup *cgrp = of->kn->parent->priv;
3347 struct cftype *cft = of->kn->priv;
3348 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
3349 int ret;
3350
3351 /*
3352 * If namespaces are delegation boundaries, disallow writes to
3353 * files in an non-init namespace root from inside the namespace
3354 * except for the files explicitly marked delegatable -
3355 * cgroup.procs and cgroup.subtree_control.
3356 */
3357 if ((cgrp->root->flags & CGRP_ROOT_NS_DELEGATE) &&
3358 !(cft->flags & CFTYPE_NS_DELEGATABLE) &&
3359 ns != &init_cgroup_ns && ns->root_cset->dfl_cgrp == cgrp)
3360 return -EPERM;
3361
3362 if (cft->write)
3363 return cft->write(of, buf, nbytes, off);
3364
3365 /*
3366 * kernfs guarantees that a file isn't deleted with operations in
3367 * flight, which means that the matching css is and stays alive and
3368 * doesn't need to be pinned. The RCU locking is not necessary
3369 * either. It's just for the convenience of using cgroup_css().
3370 */
3371 rcu_read_lock();
3372 css = cgroup_css(cgrp, cft->ss);
3373 rcu_read_unlock();
3374
3375 if (cft->write_u64) {
3376 unsigned long long v;
3377 ret = kstrtoull(buf, 0, &v);
3378 if (!ret)
3379 ret = cft->write_u64(css, cft, v);
3380 } else if (cft->write_s64) {
3381 long long v;
3382 ret = kstrtoll(buf, 0, &v);
3383 if (!ret)
3384 ret = cft->write_s64(css, cft, v);
3385 } else {
3386 ret = -EINVAL;
3387 }
3388
3389 return ret ?: nbytes;
3390}

3458static int cgroup_add_file(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css, struct cgroup *cgrp,

3467 key = &cft->lockdep_key;
3468#endif
3469 kn = __kernfs_create_file(cgrp->kn, cgroup_file_name(cgrp, cft, name),
3470 cgroup_file_mode(cft), 0, cft->kf_ops, cft,

3492/**
3493 * cgroup_addrm_files - add or remove files to a cgroup directory
3494 * @css: the target css
3495 * @cgrp: the target cgroup (usually css->cgroup)
3496 * @cfts: array of cftypes to be added
3497 * @is_add: whether to add or remove
3498 *
3499 * Depending on @is_add, add or remove files defined by @cfts on @cgrp.
3500 * For removals, this function never fails.
3501 */
3502static int cgroup_addrm_files(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css,
3503 struct cgroup *cgrp, struct cftype cfts[],
3504 bool is_add)
3505{
3506 struct cftype *cft, *cft_end = NULL;
3507 int ret = 0;
3508
3509 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3510
3511restart:
3512 for (cft = cfts; cft != cft_end && cft->name[0] != '\0'; cft++) {
3513 /* does cft->flags tell us to skip this file on @cgrp? */
3514 if ((cft->flags & __CFTYPE_ONLY_ON_DFL) && !cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp))
3515 continue;
3516 if ((cft->flags & __CFTYPE_NOT_ON_DFL) && cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp))
3517 continue;
3518 if ((cft->flags & CFTYPE_NOT_ON_ROOT) && !cgroup_parent(cgrp))
3519 continue;
3520 if ((cft->flags & CFTYPE_ONLY_ON_ROOT) && cgroup_parent(cgrp))
3521 continue;
3522
3523 if (is_add) {
3524 ret = cgroup_add_file(css, cgrp, cft);
3525 if (ret) {
3526 pr_warn("%s: failed to add %s, err=%d\n",
3527 __func__, cft->name, ret);
3528 cft_end = cft;
3529 is_add = false;
3530 goto restart;
3531 }
3532 } else {
3533 cgroup_rm_file(cgrp, cft);
3534 }
3535 }
3536 return ret;
3537}
3538
3539static int cgroup_apply_cftypes(struct cftype *cfts, bool is_add)
3540{
3541 struct cgroup_subsys *ss = cfts[0].ss;
3542 struct cgroup *root = &ss->root->cgrp;
3543 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
3544 int ret = 0;
3545
3546 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3547
3548 /* add/rm files for all cgroups created before */
3549 css_for_each_descendant_pre(css, cgroup_css(root, ss)) {
3550 struct cgroup *cgrp = css->cgroup;
3551
3552 if (!(css->flags & CSS_VISIBLE))
3553 continue;
3554
3555 ret = cgroup_addrm_files(css, cgrp, cfts, is_add);
3556 if (ret)
3557 break;
3558 }
3559
3560 if (is_add && !ret)
3561 kernfs_activate(root->kn);
3562 return ret;
3563}
3564
3565static void cgroup_exit_cftypes(struct cftype *cfts)
3566{
3567 struct cftype *cft;
3568
3569 for (cft = cfts; cft->name[0] != '\0'; cft++) {
3570 /* free copy for custom atomic_write_len, see init_cftypes() */
3571 if (cft->max_write_len && cft->max_write_len != PAGE_SIZE)
3572 kfree(cft->kf_ops);
3573 cft->kf_ops = NULL;
3574 cft->ss = NULL;
3575
3576 /* revert flags set by cgroup core while adding @cfts */
3577 cft->flags &= ~(__CFTYPE_ONLY_ON_DFL | __CFTYPE_NOT_ON_DFL);
3578 }
3579}
3580
3581static int cgroup_init_cftypes(struct cgroup_subsys *ss, struct cftype *cfts)
3582{
3583 struct cftype *cft;
3584
3585 for (cft = cfts; cft->name[0] != '\0'; cft++) {
3586 struct kernfs_ops *kf_ops;
3587
3588 WARN_ON(cft->ss || cft->kf_ops);
3589
3590 if (cft->seq_start)
3591 kf_ops = &cgroup_kf_ops;
3592 else
3593 kf_ops = &cgroup_kf_single_ops;
3594
3595 /*
3596 * Ugh... if @cft wants a custom max_write_len, we need to
3597 * make a copy of kf_ops to set its atomic_write_len.
3598 */
3599 if (cft->max_write_len && cft->max_write_len != PAGE_SIZE) {
3600 kf_ops = kmemdup(kf_ops, sizeof(*kf_ops), GFP_KERNEL);
3601 if (!kf_ops) {
3602 cgroup_exit_cftypes(cfts);
3603 return -ENOMEM;
3604 }
3605 kf_ops->atomic_write_len = cft->max_write_len;
3606 }
3607
3608 cft->kf_ops = kf_ops;
3609 cft->ss = ss;
3610 }
3611
3612 return 0;
3613}

3615static int cgroup_rm_cftypes_locked(struct cftype *cfts)
3616{
3617 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3618
3619 if (!cfts || !cfts[0].ss)
3620 return -ENOENT;
3621
3622 list_del(&cfts->node);
3623 cgroup_apply_cftypes(cfts, false);
3624 cgroup_exit_cftypes(cfts);
3625 return 0;
3626}

3628/**
3629 * cgroup_rm_cftypes - remove an array of cftypes from a subsystem
3630 * @cfts: zero-length name terminated array of cftypes
3631 *
3632 * Unregister @cfts. Files described by @cfts are removed from all
3633 * existing cgroups and all future cgroups won't have them either. This
3634 * function can be called anytime whether @cfts' subsys is attached or not.
3635 *
3636 * Returns 0 on successful unregistration, -ENOENT if @cfts is not
3637 * registered.
3638 */
3639int cgroup_rm_cftypes(struct cftype *cfts)
3640{
3641 int ret;
3642
3643 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
3644 ret = cgroup_rm_cftypes_locked(cfts);
3645 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
3646 return ret;
3647}

3649/**
3650 * cgroup_add_cftypes - add an array of cftypes to a subsystem
3651 * @ss: target cgroup subsystem
3652 * @cfts: zero-length name terminated array of cftypes
3653 *
3654 * Register @cfts to @ss. Files described by @cfts are created for all
3655 * existing cgroups to which @ss is attached and all future cgroups will
3656 * have them too. This function can be called anytime whether @ss is
3657 * attached or not.
3658 *
3659 * Returns 0 on successful registration, -errno on failure. Note that this
3660 * function currently returns 0 as long as @cfts registration is successful
3661 * even if some file creation attempts on existing cgroups fail.
3662 */
3663static int cgroup_add_cftypes(struct cgroup_subsys *ss, struct cftype *cfts)
3664{
3665 int ret;
3666
3667 if (!cgroup_ssid_enabled(ss->id))
3668 return 0;
3669
3670 if (!cfts || cfts[0].name[0] == '\0')
3671 return 0;
3672
3673 ret = cgroup_init_cftypes(ss, cfts);
3674 if (ret)
3675 return ret;
3676
3677 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
3678
3679 list_add_tail(&cfts->node, &ss->cfts);
3680 ret = cgroup_apply_cftypes(cfts, true);
3681 if (ret)
3682 cgroup_rm_cftypes_locked(cfts);
3683
3684 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
3685 return ret;
3686}

3738/**
3739 * css_next_child - find the next child of a given css
3740 * @pos: the current position (%NULL to initiate traversal)
3741 * @parent: css whose children to walk
3742 *
3743 * This function returns the next child of @parent and should be called
3744 * under either cgroup_mutex or RCU read lock. The only requirement is
3745 * that @parent and @pos are accessible. The next sibling is guaranteed to
3746 * be returned regardless of their states.
3747 *
3748 * If a subsystem synchronizes ->css_online() and the start of iteration, a
3749 * css which finished ->css_online() is guaranteed to be visible in the
3750 * future iterations and will stay visible until the last reference is put.
3751 * A css which hasn't finished ->css_online() or already finished
3752 * ->css_offline() may show up during traversal. It's each subsystem's
3753 * responsibility to synchronize against on/offlining.
3754 */
3755struct cgroup_subsys_state *css_next_child(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos,
3756 struct cgroup_subsys_state *parent)
3757{
3758 struct cgroup_subsys_state *next;
3759
3760 cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
3761
3762 /*
3763 * @pos could already have been unlinked from the sibling list.
3764 * Once a cgroup is removed, its ->sibling.next is no longer
3765 * updated when its next sibling changes. CSS_RELEASED is set when
3766 * @pos is taken off list, at which time its next pointer is valid,
3767 * and, as releases are serialized, the one pointed to by the next
3768 * pointer is guaranteed to not have started release yet. This
3769 * implies that if we observe !CSS_RELEASED on @pos in this RCU
3770 * critical section, the one pointed to by its next pointer is
3771 * guaranteed to not have finished its RCU grace period even if we
3772 * have dropped rcu_read_lock() inbetween iterations.
3773 *
3774 * If @pos has CSS_RELEASED set, its next pointer can't be
3775 * dereferenced; however, as each css is given a monotonically
3776 * increasing unique serial number and always appended to the
3777 * sibling list, the next one can be found by walking the parent's
3778 * children until the first css with higher serial number than
3779 * @pos's. While this path can be slower, it happens iff iteration
3780 * races against release and the race window is very small.
3781 */
3782 if (!pos) {
3783 next = list_entry_rcu(parent->children.next, struct cgroup_subsys_state, sibling);
3784 } else if (likely(!(pos->flags & CSS_RELEASED))) {
3785 next = list_entry_rcu(pos->sibling.next, struct cgroup_subsys_state, sibling);
3786 } else {
3787 list_for_each_entry_rcu(next, &parent->children, sibling)
3788 if (next->serial_nr > pos->serial_nr)
3789 break;
3790 }
3791
3792 /*
3793 * @next, if not pointing to the head, can be dereferenced and is
3794 * the next sibling.
3795 */
3796 if (&next->sibling != &parent->children)
3797 return next;
3798 return NULL;
3799}
3800
3801/**
3802 * css_next_descendant_pre - find the next descendant for pre-order walk
3803 * @pos: the current position (%NULL to initiate traversal)
3804 * @root: css whose descendants to walk
3805 *
3806 * To be used by css_for_each_descendant_pre(). Find the next descendant
3807 * to visit for pre-order traversal of @root's descendants. @root is
3808 * included in the iteration and the first node to be visited.
3809 *
3810 * While this function requires cgroup_mutex or RCU read locking, it
3811 * doesn't require the whole traversal to be contained in a single critical
3812 * section. This function will return the correct next descendant as long
3813 * as both @pos and @root are accessible and @pos is a descendant of @root.
3814 *
3815 * If a subsystem synchronizes ->css_online() and the start of iteration, a
3816 * css which finished ->css_online() is guaranteed to be visible in the
3817 * future iterations and will stay visible until the last reference is put.
3818 * A css which hasn't finished ->css_online() or already finished
3819 * ->css_offline() may show up during traversal. It's each subsystem's
3820 * responsibility to synchronize against on/offlining.
3821 */
3822struct cgroup_subsys_state *
3823css_next_descendant_pre(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos,
3824 struct cgroup_subsys_state *root)
3825{
3826 struct cgroup_subsys_state *next;
3827
3828 cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
3829
3830 /* if first iteration, visit @root */
3831 if (!pos)
3832 return root;
3833
3834 /* visit the first child if exists */
3835 next = css_next_child(NULL, pos);
3836 if (next)
3837 return next;
3838
3839 /* no child, visit my or the closest ancestor's next sibling */
3840 while (pos != root) {
3841 next = css_next_child(pos, pos->parent);
3842 if (next)
3843 return next;
3844 pos = pos->parent;
3845 }
3846
3847 return NULL;
3848}
3849
3850/**
3851 * css_rightmost_descendant - return the rightmost descendant of a css
3852 * @pos: css of interest
3853 *
3854 * Return the rightmost descendant of @pos. If there's no descendant, @pos
3855 * is returned. This can be used during pre-order traversal to skip
3856 * subtree of @pos.
3857 *
3858 * While this function requires cgroup_mutex or RCU read locking, it
3859 * doesn't require the whole traversal to be contained in a single critical
3860 * section. This function will return the correct rightmost descendant as
3861 * long as @pos is accessible.
3862 */
3863struct cgroup_subsys_state *
3864css_rightmost_descendant(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos)
3865{
3866 struct cgroup_subsys_state *last, *tmp;
3867
3868 cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
3869
3870 do {
3871 last = pos;
3872 /* ->prev isn't RCU safe, walk ->next till the end */
3873 pos = NULL;
3874 css_for_each_child(tmp, last)
3875 pos = tmp;
3876 } while (pos);
3877
3878 return last;
3879}
3880
3881static struct cgroup_subsys_state *
3882css_leftmost_descendant(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos)
3883{
3884 struct cgroup_subsys_state *last;
3885
3886 do {
3887 last = pos;
3888 pos = css_next_child(NULL, pos);
3889 } while (pos);
3890
3891 return last;
3892}
3893
3894/**
3895 * css_next_descendant_post - find the next descendant for post-order walk
3896 * @pos: the current position (%NULL to initiate traversal)
3897 * @root: css whose descendants to walk
3898 *
3899 * To be used by css_for_each_descendant_post(). Find the next descendant
3900 * to visit for post-order traversal of @root's descendants. @root is
3901 * included in the iteration and the last node to be visited.
3902 *
3903 * While this function requires cgroup_mutex or RCU read locking, it
3904 * doesn't require the whole traversal to be contained in a single critical
3905 * section. This function will return the correct next descendant as long
3906 * as both @pos and @cgroup are accessible and @pos is a descendant of
3907 * @cgroup.
3908 *
3909 * If a subsystem synchronizes ->css_online() and the start of iteration, a
3910 * css which finished ->css_online() is guaranteed to be visible in the
3911 * future iterations and will stay visible until the last reference is put.
3912 * A css which hasn't finished ->css_online() or already finished
3913 * ->css_offline() may show up during traversal. It's each subsystem's
3914 * responsibility to synchronize against on/offlining.
3915 */
3916struct cgroup_subsys_state *
3917css_next_descendant_post(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos,
3918 struct cgroup_subsys_state *root)
3919{
3920 struct cgroup_subsys_state *next;
3921
3922 cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
3923
3924 /* if first iteration, visit leftmost descendant which may be @root */
3925 if (!pos)
3926 return css_leftmost_descendant(root);
3927
3928 /* if we visited @root, we're done */
3929 if (pos == root)
3930 return NULL;
3931
3932 /* if there's an unvisited sibling, visit its leftmost descendant */
3933 next = css_next_child(pos, pos->parent);
3934 if (next)
3935 return css_leftmost_descendant(next);
3936
3937 /* no sibling left, visit parent */
3938 return pos->parent;
3939}
3940
3941/**
3942 * css_has_online_children - does a css have online children
3943 * @css: the target css
3944 *
3945 * Returns %true if @css has any online children; otherwise, %false. This
3946 * function can be called from any context but the caller is responsible
3947 * for synchronizing against on/offlining as necessary.
3948 */
3949bool css_has_online_children(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
3950{
3951 struct cgroup_subsys_state *child;
3952 bool ret = false;
3953
3954 rcu_read_lock();
3955 css_for_each_child(child, css) {
3956 if (child->flags & CSS_ONLINE) {
3957 ret = true;
3958 break;
3959 }
3960 }
3961 rcu_read_unlock();
3962 return ret;
3963}
3964
3965static struct css_set *css_task_iter_next_css_set(struct css_task_iter *it)
3966{
3967 struct list_head *l;
3968 struct cgrp_cset_link *link;
3969 struct css_set *cset;
3970
3971 lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
3972
3973 /* find the next threaded cset */
3974 if (it->tcset_pos) {
3975 l = it->tcset_pos->next;
3976
3977 if (l != it->tcset_head) {
3978 it->tcset_pos = l;
3979 return container_of(l, struct css_set,
3980 threaded_csets_node);
3981 }
3982
3983 it->tcset_pos = NULL;
3984 }
3985
3986 /* find the next cset */
3987 l = it->cset_pos;
3988 l = l->next;
3989 if (l == it->cset_head) {
3990 it->cset_pos = NULL;
3991 return NULL;
3992 }
3993
3994 if (it->ss) {
3995 cset = container_of(l, struct css_set, e_cset_node[it->ss->id]);
3996 } else {
3997 link = list_entry(l, struct cgrp_cset_link, cset_link);
3998 cset = link->cset;
3999 }
4000
4001 it->cset_pos = l;
4002
4003 /* initialize threaded css_set walking */
4004 if (it->flags & CSS_TASK_ITER_THREADED) {
4005 if (it->cur_dcset)
4006 put_css_set_locked(it->cur_dcset);
4007 it->cur_dcset = cset;
4008 get_css_set(cset);
4009
4010 it->tcset_head = &cset->threaded_csets;
4011 it->tcset_pos = &cset->threaded_csets;
4012 }
4013
4014 return cset;
4015}
4016
4017/**
4018 * css_task_iter_advance_css_set - advance a task itererator to the next css_set
4019 * @it: the iterator to advance
4020 *
4021 * Advance @it to the next css_set to walk.
4022 */
4023static void css_task_iter_advance_css_set(struct css_task_iter *it)
4024{
4025 struct css_set *cset;
4026
4027 lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
4028
4029 /* Advance to the next non-empty css_set */
4030 do {
4031 cset = css_task_iter_next_css_set(it);
4032 if (!cset) {
4033 it->task_pos = NULL;
4034 return;
4035 }
4036 } while (!css_set_populated(cset));
4037
4038 if (!list_empty(&cset->tasks))
4039 it->task_pos = cset->tasks.next;
4040 else
4041 it->task_pos = cset->mg_tasks.next;
4042
4043 it->tasks_head = &cset->tasks;
4044 it->mg_tasks_head = &cset->mg_tasks;
4045
4046 /*
4047 * We don't keep css_sets locked across iteration steps and thus
4048 * need to take steps to ensure that iteration can be resumed after
4049 * the lock is re-acquired. Iteration is performed at two levels -
4050 * css_sets and tasks in them.
4051 *
4052 * Once created, a css_set never leaves its cgroup lists, so a
4053 * pinned css_set is guaranteed to stay put and we can resume
4054 * iteration afterwards.
4055 *
4056 * Tasks may leave @cset across iteration steps. This is resolved
4057 * by registering each iterator with the css_set currently being
4058 * walked and making css_set_move_task() advance iterators whose
4059 * next task is leaving.
4060 */
4061 if (it->cur_cset) {
4062 list_del(&it->iters_node);
4063 put_css_set_locked(it->cur_cset);
4064 }
4065 get_css_set(cset);
4066 it->cur_cset = cset;
4067 list_add(&it->iters_node, &cset->task_iters);
4068}
4069
4070static void css_task_iter_advance(struct css_task_iter *it)
4071{
4072 struct list_head *next;
4073
4074 lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
4075repeat:
4076 /*
4077 * Advance iterator to find next entry. cset->tasks is consumed
4078 * first and then ->mg_tasks. After ->mg_tasks, we move onto the
4079 * next cset.
4080 */
4081 next = it->task_pos->next;
4082
4083 if (next == it->tasks_head)
4084 next = it->mg_tasks_head->next;
4085
4086 if (next == it->mg_tasks_head)
4087 css_task_iter_advance_css_set(it);
4088 else
4089 it->task_pos = next;
4090
4091 /* if PROCS, skip over tasks which aren't group leaders */
4092 if ((it->flags & CSS_TASK_ITER_PROCS) && it->task_pos &&
4093 !thread_group_leader(list_entry(it->task_pos, struct task_struct,
4094 cg_list)))
4095 goto repeat;
4096}
4097
4098/**
4099 * css_task_iter_start - initiate task iteration
4100 * @css: the css to walk tasks of
4101 * @flags: CSS_TASK_ITER_* flags
4102 * @it: the task iterator to use
4103 *
4104 * Initiate iteration through the tasks of @css. The caller can call
4105 * css_task_iter_next() to walk through the tasks until the function
4106 * returns NULL. On completion of iteration, css_task_iter_end() must be
4107 * called.
4108 */
4109void css_task_iter_start(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css, unsigned int flags,
4110 struct css_task_iter *it)
4111{
4112 /* no one should try to iterate before mounting cgroups */
4113 WARN_ON_ONCE(!use_task_css_set_links);
4114
4115 memset(it, 0, sizeof(*it));
4116
4117 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4118
4119 it->ss = css->ss;
4120 it->flags = flags;
4121
4122 if (it->ss)
4123 it->cset_pos = &css->cgroup->e_csets[css->ss->id];
4124 else
4125 it->cset_pos = &css->cgroup->cset_links;
4126
4127 it->cset_head = it->cset_pos;
4128
4129 css_task_iter_advance_css_set(it);
4130
4131 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4132}
4133
4134/**
4135 * css_task_iter_next - return the next task for the iterator
4136 * @it: the task iterator being iterated
4137 *
4138 * The "next" function for task iteration. @it should have been
4139 * initialized via css_task_iter_start(). Returns NULL when the iteration
4140 * reaches the end.
4141 */
4142struct task_struct *css_task_iter_next(struct css_task_iter *it)
4143{
4144 if (it->cur_task) {
4145 put_task_struct(it->cur_task);
4146 it->cur_task = NULL;
4147 }
4148
4149 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4150
4151 if (it->task_pos) {
4152 it->cur_task = list_entry(it->task_pos, struct task_struct,
4153 cg_list);
4154 get_task_struct(it->cur_task);
4155 css_task_iter_advance(it);
4156 }
4157
4158 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4159
4160 return it->cur_task;
4161}
4162
4163/**
4164 * css_task_iter_end - finish task iteration
4165 * @it: the task iterator to finish
4166 *
4167 * Finish task iteration started by css_task_iter_start().
4168 */
4169void css_task_iter_end(struct css_task_iter *it)
4170{
4171 if (it->cur_cset) {
4172 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4173 list_del(&it->iters_node);
4174 put_css_set_locked(it->cur_cset);
4175 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4176 }
4177
4178 if (it->cur_dcset)
4179 put_css_set(it->cur_dcset);
4180
4181 if (it->cur_task)
4182 put_task_struct(it->cur_task);
4183}

4185static void cgroup_procs_release(struct kernfs_open_file *of)
4186{
4187 if (of->priv) {
4188 css_task_iter_end(of->priv);
4189 kfree(of->priv);
4190 }
4191}

4194{
4195 struct kernfs_open_file *of = s->private;
4196 struct css_task_iter *it = of->priv;
4197

4200
4201static void *__cgroup_procs_start(struct seq_file *s, loff_t *pos,
4202 unsigned int iter_flags)
4203{
4204 struct kernfs_open_file *of = s->private;
4205 struct cgroup *cgrp = seq_css(s)->cgroup;
4206 struct css_task_iter *it = of->priv;
4207
4208 /*
4209 * When a seq_file is seeked, it's always traversed sequentially
4210 * from position 0, so we can simply keep iterating on !0 *pos.
4211 */
4212 if (!it) {
4213 if (WARN_ON_ONCE((*pos)++))
4214 return ERR_PTR(-EINVAL);
4215
4216 it = kzalloc(sizeof(*it), GFP_KERNEL);
4217 if (!it)
4218 return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
4219 of->priv = it;
4220 css_task_iter_start(&cgrp->self, iter_flags, it);
4221 } else if (!(*pos)++) {
4222 css_task_iter_end(it);
4223 css_task_iter_start(&cgrp->self, iter_flags, it);
4224 }
4225
4226 return cgroup_procs_next(s, NULL, NULL);
4227}
4228
4229static void *cgroup_procs_start(struct seq_file *s, loff_t *pos)
4230{
4231 struct cgroup *cgrp = seq_css(s)->cgroup;
4232
4233 /*
4234 * All processes of a threaded subtree belong to the domain cgroup
4235 * of the subtree. Only threads can be distributed across the
4236 * subtree. Reject reads on cgroup.procs in the subtree proper.
4237 * They're always empty anyway.
4238 */
4239 if (cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
4240 return ERR_PTR(-EOPNOTSUPP);
4241
4242 return __cgroup_procs_start(s, pos, CSS_TASK_ITER_PROCS |
4243 CSS_TASK_ITER_THREADED);
4244}

4249 return 0;

4252static int cgroup_procs_write_permission(struct cgroup *src_cgrp,
4253 struct cgroup *dst_cgrp,
4254 struct super_block *sb)
4255{
4256 struct cgroup_namespace *ns = current->nsproxy->cgroup_ns;
4257 struct cgroup *com_cgrp = src_cgrp;
4258 struct inode *inode;
4259 int ret;
4260
4261 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4262
4263 /* find the common ancestor */
4264 while (!cgroup_is_descendant(dst_cgrp, com_cgrp))
4265 com_cgrp = cgroup_parent(com_cgrp);
4266
4267 /* %current should be authorized to migrate to the common ancestor */
4268 inode = kernfs_get_inode(sb, com_cgrp->procs_file.kn);
4269 if (!inode)
4270 return -ENOMEM;
4271
4272 ret = inode_permission(inode, MAY_WRITE);
4273 iput(inode);
4274 if (ret)
4275 return ret;
4276
4277 /*
4278 * If namespaces are delegation boundaries, %current must be able
4279 * to see both source and destination cgroups from its namespace.
4280 */
4281 if ((cgrp_dfl_root.flags & CGRP_ROOT_NS_DELEGATE) &&
4282 (!cgroup_is_descendant(src_cgrp, ns->root_cset->dfl_cgrp) ||
4283 !cgroup_is_descendant(dst_cgrp, ns->root_cset->dfl_cgrp)))
4284 return -ENOENT;
4285
4286 return 0;
4287}
4288
4289static ssize_t cgroup_procs_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of,
4290 char *buf, size_t nbytes, loff_t off)
4291{
4292 struct cgroup *src_cgrp, *dst_cgrp;
4293 struct task_struct *task;
4294 ssize_t ret;
4295
4296 dst_cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, false);
4297 if (!dst_cgrp)
4298 return -ENODEV;
4299
4300 task = cgroup_procs_write_start(buf, true);
4301 ret = PTR_ERR_OR_ZERO(task);
4302 if (ret)
4303 goto out_unlock;
4304
4305 /* find the source cgroup */
4306 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4307 src_cgrp = task_cgroup_from_root(task, &cgrp_dfl_root);
4308 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4309
4310 ret = cgroup_procs_write_permission(src_cgrp, dst_cgrp,
4311 of->file->f_path.dentry->d_sb);
4312 if (ret)
4313 goto out_finish;
4314
4315 ret = cgroup_attach_task(dst_cgrp, task, true);
4316
4317out_finish:
4318 cgroup_procs_write_finish(task);
4319out_unlock:
4320 cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);
4321
4322 return ret ?: nbytes;
4323}

4325static void *cgroup_threads_start(struct seq_file *s, loff_t *pos)
4326{

4328}
4329
4330static ssize_t cgroup_threads_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of,
4331 char *buf, size_t nbytes, loff_t off)
4332{
4333 struct cgroup *src_cgrp, *dst_cgrp;
4334 struct task_struct *task;
4335 ssize_t ret;
4336
4337 buf = strstrip(buf);
4338
4339 dst_cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, false);
4340 if (!dst_cgrp)
4341 return -ENODEV;
4342
4343 task = cgroup_procs_write_start(buf, false);
4344 ret = PTR_ERR_OR_ZERO(task);
4345 if (ret)
4346 goto out_unlock;
4347
4348 /* find the source cgroup */
4349 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4350 src_cgrp = task_cgroup_from_root(task, &cgrp_dfl_root);
4351 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4352
4353 /* thread migrations follow the cgroup.procs delegation rule */
4354 ret = cgroup_procs_write_permission(src_cgrp, dst_cgrp,
4355 of->file->f_path.dentry->d_sb);
4356 if (ret)
4357 goto out_finish;
4358
4359 /* and must be contained in the same domain */
4360 ret = -EOPNOTSUPP;
4361 if (src_cgrp->dom_cgrp != dst_cgrp->dom_cgrp)
4362 goto out_finish;
4363
4364 ret = cgroup_attach_task(dst_cgrp, task, false);
4365
4366out_finish:
4367 cgroup_procs_write_finish(task);
4368out_unlock:
4369 cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);
4370
4371 return ret ?: nbytes;
4372}

4433/*
4434 * css destruction is four-stage process.
4435 *
4436 * 1. Destruction starts. Killing of the percpu_ref is initiated.
4437 * Implemented in kill_css().
4438 *
4439 * 2. When the percpu_ref is confirmed to be visible as killed on all CPUs
4440 * and thus css_tryget_online() is guaranteed to fail, the css can be
4441 * offlined by invoking offline_css(). After offlining, the base ref is
4442 * put. Implemented in css_killed_work_fn().
4443 *
4444 * 3. When the percpu_ref reaches zero, the only possible remaining
4445 * accessors are inside RCU read sections. css_release() schedules the
4446 * RCU callback.
4447 *
4448 * 4. After the grace period, the css can be freed. Implemented in
4449 * css_free_work_fn().
4450 *
4451 * It is actually hairier because both step 2 and 4 require process context
4452 * and thus involve punting to css->destroy_work adding two additional
4453 * steps to the already complex sequence.
4454 */
4455static void css_free_work_fn(struct work_struct *work)
4456{
4457 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
4458 container_of(work, struct cgroup_subsys_state, destroy_work);
4459 struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
4460 struct cgroup *cgrp = css->cgroup;
4461
4462 percpu_ref_exit(&css->refcnt);
4463
4464 if (ss) {
4465 /* css free path */
4466 struct cgroup_subsys_state *parent = css->parent;
4467 int id = css->id;
4468
4469 ss->css_free(css);
4470 cgroup_idr_remove(&ss->css_idr, id);
4471 cgroup_put(cgrp);
4472
4473 if (parent)
4474 css_put(parent);
4475 } else {
4476 /* cgroup free path */
4477 atomic_dec(&cgrp->root->nr_cgrps);
4478 cgroup1_pidlist_destroy_all(cgrp);
4479 cancel_work_sync(&cgrp->release_agent_work);
4480
4481 if (cgroup_parent(cgrp)) {
4482 /*
4483 * We get a ref to the parent, and put the ref when
4484 * this cgroup is being freed, so it's guaranteed
4485 * that the parent won't be destroyed before its
4486 * children.
4487 */
4488 cgroup_put(cgroup_parent(cgrp));
4489 kernfs_put(cgrp->kn);
4490 kfree(cgrp);
4491 } else {
4492 /*
4493 * This is root cgroup's refcnt reaching zero,
4494 * which indicates that the root should be
4495 * released.
4496 */
4497 cgroup_destroy_root(cgrp->root);
4498 }
4499 }
4500}
4501
4502static void css_free_rcu_fn(struct rcu_head *rcu_head)
4503{
4504 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
4505 container_of(rcu_head, struct cgroup_subsys_state, rcu_head);
4506
4507 INIT_WORK(&css->destroy_work, css_free_work_fn);
4508 queue_work(cgroup_destroy_wq, &css->destroy_work);
4509}
4510
4511static void css_release_work_fn(struct work_struct *work)
4512{
4513 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
4514 container_of(work, struct cgroup_subsys_state, destroy_work);
4515 struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
4516 struct cgroup *cgrp = css->cgroup;
4517
4518 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
4519
4520 css->flags |= CSS_RELEASED;
4521 list_del_rcu(&css->sibling);
4522
4523 if (ss) {
4524 /* css release path */
4525 cgroup_idr_replace(&ss->css_idr, NULL, css->id);
4526 if (ss->css_released)
4527 ss->css_released(css);
4528 } else {
4529 struct cgroup *tcgrp;
4530
4531 /* cgroup release path */
4532 trace_cgroup_release(cgrp);
4533
4534 for (tcgrp = cgroup_parent(cgrp); tcgrp;
4535 tcgrp = cgroup_parent(tcgrp))
4536 tcgrp->nr_dying_descendants--;
4537
4538 cgroup_idr_remove(&cgrp->root->cgroup_idr, cgrp->id);
4539 cgrp->id = -1;
4540
4541 /*
4542 * There are two control paths which try to determine
4543 * cgroup from dentry without going through kernfs -
4544 * cgroupstats_build() and css_tryget_online_from_dir().
4545 * Those are supported by RCU protecting clearing of
4546 * cgrp->kn->priv backpointer.
4547 */
4548 if (cgrp->kn)
4549 RCU_INIT_POINTER(*(void __rcu __force **)&cgrp->kn->priv,
4550 NULL);
4551
4552 cgroup_bpf_put(cgrp);
4553 }
4554
4555 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
4556
4557 call_rcu(&css->rcu_head, css_free_rcu_fn);
4558}
4559
4560static void css_release(struct percpu_ref *ref)
4561{
4562 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
4563 container_of(ref, struct cgroup_subsys_state, refcnt);
4564
4565 INIT_WORK(&css->destroy_work, css_release_work_fn);
4566 queue_work(cgroup_destroy_wq, &css->destroy_work);
4567}

4569static void init_and_link_css(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css,
4570 struct cgroup_subsys *ss, struct cgroup *cgrp)
4571{
4572 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4573
4574 cgroup_get_live(cgrp);
4575
4576 memset(css, 0, sizeof(*css));
4577 css->cgroup = cgrp;
4578 css->ss = ss;
4579 css->id = -1;
4580 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&css->sibling);
4581 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&css->children);
4582 css->serial_nr = css_serial_nr_next++;
4583 atomic_set(&css->online_cnt, 0);
4584
4585 if (cgroup_parent(cgrp)) {
4586 css->parent = cgroup_css(cgroup_parent(cgrp), ss);
4587 css_get(css->parent);
4588 }
4589
4590 BUG_ON(cgroup_css(cgrp, ss));
4591}
4592
4593/* invoke ->css_online() on a new CSS and mark it online if successful */
4594static int online_css(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
4595{
4596 struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
4597 int ret = 0;
4598
4599 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4600
4601 if (ss->css_online)
4602 ret = ss->css_online(css);
4603 if (!ret) {
4604 css->flags |= CSS_ONLINE;
4605 rcu_assign_pointer(css->cgroup->subsys[ss->id], css);
4606
4607 atomic_inc(&css->online_cnt);
4608 if (css->parent)
4609 atomic_inc(&css->parent->online_cnt);
4610 }
4611 return ret;
4612}
4613
4614/* if the CSS is online, invoke ->css_offline() on it and mark it offline */
4615static void offline_css(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
4616{
4617 struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
4618
4619 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4620
4621 if (!(css->flags & CSS_ONLINE))
4622 return;
4623
4624 if (ss->css_offline)
4625 ss->css_offline(css);
4626
4627 css->flags &= ~CSS_ONLINE;
4628 RCU_INIT_POINTER(css->cgroup->subsys[ss->id], NULL);
4629
4630 wake_up_all(&css->cgroup->offline_waitq);
4631}
4632
4633/**
4634 * css_create - create a cgroup_subsys_state
4635 * @cgrp: the cgroup new css will be associated with
4636 * @ss: the subsys of new css
4637 *
4638 * Create a new css associated with @cgrp - @ss pair. On success, the new
4639 * css is online and installed in @cgrp. This function doesn't create the
4640 * interface files. Returns 0 on success, -errno on failure.
4641 */
4642static struct cgroup_subsys_state *css_create(struct cgroup *cgrp,
4643 struct cgroup_subsys *ss)
4644{
4645 struct cgroup *parent = cgroup_parent(cgrp);
4646 struct cgroup_subsys_state *parent_css = cgroup_css(parent, ss);
4647 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
4648 int err;
4649
4650 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4651
4652 css = ss->css_alloc(parent_css);
4653 if (!css)
4654 css = ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
4655 if (IS_ERR(css))
4656 return css;
4657
4658 init_and_link_css(css, ss, cgrp);
4659
4660 err = percpu_ref_init(&css->refcnt, css_release, 0, GFP_KERNEL);
4661 if (err)
4662 goto err_free_css;
4663
4664 err = cgroup_idr_alloc(&ss->css_idr, NULL, 2, 0, GFP_KERNEL);
4665 if (err < 0)
4666 goto err_free_css;
4667 css->id = err;
4668
4669 /* @css is ready to be brought online now, make it visible */
4670 list_add_tail_rcu(&css->sibling, &parent_css->children);
4671 cgroup_idr_replace(&ss->css_idr, css, css->id);
4672
4673 err = online_css(css);
4674 if (err)
4675 goto err_list_del;
4676
4677 if (ss->broken_hierarchy && !ss->warned_broken_hierarchy &&
4678 cgroup_parent(parent)) {
4679 pr_warn("%s (%d) created nested cgroup for controller \"%s\" which has incomplete hierarchy support. Nested cgroups may change behavior in the future.\n",
4680 current->comm, current->pid, ss->name);
4681 if (!strcmp(ss->name, "memory"))
4682 pr_warn("\"memory\" requires setting use_hierarchy to 1 on the root\n");
4683 ss->warned_broken_hierarchy = true;
4684 }
4685
4686 return css;
4687
4688err_list_del:
4689 list_del_rcu(&css->sibling);
4690err_free_css:
4691 call_rcu(&css->rcu_head, css_free_rcu_fn);
4692 return ERR_PTR(err);
4693}
4694
4695/*
4696 * The returned cgroup is fully initialized including its control mask, but
4697 * it isn't associated with its kernfs_node and doesn't have the control
4698 * mask applied.
4699 */
4700static struct cgroup *cgroup_create(struct cgroup *parent)
4701{
4702 struct cgroup_root *root = parent->root;
4703 struct cgroup *cgrp, *tcgrp;
4704 int level = parent->level + 1;
4705 int ret;
4706
4707 /* allocate the cgroup and its ID, 0 is reserved for the root */
4708 cgrp = kzalloc(sizeof(*cgrp) +
4709 sizeof(cgrp->ancestor_ids[0]) * (level + 1), GFP_KERNEL);
4710 if (!cgrp)
4711 return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
4712
4713 ret = percpu_ref_init(&cgrp->self.refcnt, css_release, 0, GFP_KERNEL);
4714 if (ret)
4715 goto out_free_cgrp;
4716
4717 /*
4718 * Temporarily set the pointer to NULL, so idr_find() won't return
4719 * a half-baked cgroup.
4720 */
4721 cgrp->id = cgroup_idr_alloc(&root->cgroup_idr, NULL, 2, 0, GFP_KERNEL);
4722 if (cgrp->id < 0) {
4723 ret = -ENOMEM;
4724 goto out_cancel_ref;
4725 }
4726
4727 init_cgroup_housekeeping(cgrp);
4728
4729 cgrp->self.parent = &parent->self;
4730 cgrp->root = root;
4731 cgrp->level = level;
4732
4733 for (tcgrp = cgrp; tcgrp; tcgrp = cgroup_parent(tcgrp)) {
4734 cgrp->ancestor_ids[tcgrp->level] = tcgrp->id;
4735
4736 if (tcgrp != cgrp)
4737 tcgrp->nr_descendants++;
4738 }
4739
4740 if (notify_on_release(parent))
4741 set_bit(CGRP_NOTIFY_ON_RELEASE, &cgrp->flags);
4742
4743 if (test_bit(CGRP_CPUSET_CLONE_CHILDREN, &parent->flags))
4744 set_bit(CGRP_CPUSET_CLONE_CHILDREN, &cgrp->flags);
4745
4746 cgrp->self.serial_nr = css_serial_nr_next++;
4747
4748 /* allocation complete, commit to creation */
4749 list_add_tail_rcu(&cgrp->self.sibling, &cgroup_parent(cgrp)->self.children);
4750 atomic_inc(&root->nr_cgrps);
4751 cgroup_get_live(parent);
4752
4753 /*
4754 * @cgrp is now fully operational. If something fails after this
4755 * point, it'll be released via the normal destruction path.
4756 */
4757 cgroup_idr_replace(&root->cgroup_idr, cgrp, cgrp->id);
4758
4759 /*
4760 * On the default hierarchy, a child doesn't automatically inherit
4761 * subtree_control from the parent. Each is configured manually.
4762 */
4763 if (!cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp))
4764 cgrp->subtree_control = cgroup_control(cgrp);
4765
4766 if (parent)
4767 cgroup_bpf_inherit(cgrp, parent);
4768
4769 cgroup_propagate_control(cgrp);
4770
4771 return cgrp;
4772
4773out_cancel_ref:
4774 percpu_ref_exit(&cgrp->self.refcnt);
4775out_free_cgrp:
4776 kfree(cgrp);
4777 return ERR_PTR(ret);
4778}
4779
4780static bool cgroup_check_hierarchy_limits(struct cgroup *parent)
4781{
4782 struct cgroup *cgroup;
4783 int ret = false;
4784 int level = 1;
4785
4786 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4787
4788 for (cgroup = parent; cgroup; cgroup = cgroup_parent(cgroup)) {
4789 if (cgroup->nr_descendants >= cgroup->max_descendants)
4790 goto fail;
4791
4792 if (level > cgroup->max_depth)
4793 goto fail;
4794
4795 level++;
4796 }
4797
4798 ret = true;
4799fail:
4800 return ret;
4801}
4802
4803int cgroup_mkdir(struct kernfs_node *parent_kn, const char *name, umode_t mode)
4804{
4805 struct cgroup *parent, *cgrp;
4806 struct kernfs_node *kn;
4807 int ret;
4808
4809 /* do not accept '\n' to prevent making /proc/<pid>/cgroup unparsable */
4810 if (strchr(name, '\n'))
4811 return -EINVAL;
4812
4813 parent = cgroup_kn_lock_live(parent_kn, false);
4814 if (!parent)
4815 return -ENODEV;
4816
4817 if (!cgroup_check_hierarchy_limits(parent)) {
4818 ret = -EAGAIN;
4819 goto out_unlock;
4820 }
4821
4822 cgrp = cgroup_create(parent);
4823 if (IS_ERR(cgrp)) {
4824 ret = PTR_ERR(cgrp);
4825 goto out_unlock;
4826 }
4827
4828 /* create the directory */
4829 kn = kernfs_create_dir(parent->kn, name, mode, cgrp);
4830 if (IS_ERR(kn)) {
4831 ret = PTR_ERR(kn);
4832 goto out_destroy;
4833 }
4834 cgrp->kn = kn;
4835
4836 /*
4837 * This extra ref will be put in cgroup_free_fn() and guarantees
4838 * that @cgrp->kn is always accessible.
4839 */
4840 kernfs_get(kn);
4841
4842 ret = cgroup_kn_set_ugid(kn);
4843 if (ret)
4844 goto out_destroy;
4845
4846 ret = css_populate_dir(&cgrp->self);
4847 if (ret)
4848 goto out_destroy;
4849
4850 ret = cgroup_apply_control_enable(cgrp);
4851 if (ret)
4852 goto out_destroy;
4853
4854 trace_cgroup_mkdir(cgrp);
4855
4856 /* let's create and online css's */
4857 kernfs_activate(kn);
4858
4859 ret = 0;
4860 goto out_unlock;
4861
4862out_destroy:
4863 cgroup_destroy_locked(cgrp);
4864out_unlock:
4865 cgroup_kn_unlock(parent_kn);
4866 return ret;
4867}
4868
4869/*
4870 * This is called when the refcnt of a css is confirmed to be killed.
4871 * css_tryget_online() is now guaranteed to fail. Tell the subsystem to
4872 * initate destruction and put the css ref from kill_css().
4873 */
4874static void css_killed_work_fn(struct work_struct *work)
4875{
4876 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
4877 container_of(work, struct cgroup_subsys_state, destroy_work);
4878
4879 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
4880
4881 do {
4882 offline_css(css);
4883 css_put(css);
4884 /* @css can't go away while we're holding cgroup_mutex */
4885 css = css->parent;
4886 } while (css && atomic_dec_and_test(&css->online_cnt));
4887
4888 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
4889}
4890
4891/* css kill confirmation processing requires process context, bounce */
4892static void css_killed_ref_fn(struct percpu_ref *ref)
4893{
4894 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
4895 container_of(ref, struct cgroup_subsys_state, refcnt);
4896
4897 if (atomic_dec_and_test(&css->online_cnt)) {
4898 INIT_WORK(&css->destroy_work, css_killed_work_fn);
4899 queue_work(cgroup_destroy_wq, &css->destroy_work);
4900 }
4901}
4902
4903/**
4904 * kill_css - destroy a css
4905 * @css: css to destroy
4906 *
4907 * This function initiates destruction of @css by removing cgroup interface
4908 * files and putting its base reference. ->css_offline() will be invoked
4909 * asynchronously once css_tryget_online() is guaranteed to fail and when
4910 * the reference count reaches zero, @css will be released.
4911 */
4912static void kill_css(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
4913{
4914 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4915
4916 if (css->flags & CSS_DYING)
4917 return;
4918
4919 css->flags |= CSS_DYING;
4920
4921 /*
4922 * This must happen before css is disassociated with its cgroup.
4923 * See seq_css() for details.
4924 */
4925 css_clear_dir(css);
4926
4927 /*
4928 * Killing would put the base ref, but we need to keep it alive
4929 * until after ->css_offline().
4930 */
4931 css_get(css);
4932
4933 /*
4934 * cgroup core guarantees that, by the time ->css_offline() is
4935 * invoked, no new css reference will be given out via
4936 * css_tryget_online(). We can't simply call percpu_ref_kill() and
4937 * proceed to offlining css's because percpu_ref_kill() doesn't
4938 * guarantee that the ref is seen as killed on all CPUs on return.
4939 *
4940 * Use percpu_ref_kill_and_confirm() to get notifications as each
4941 * css is confirmed to be seen as killed on all CPUs.
4942 */
4943 percpu_ref_kill_and_confirm(&css->refcnt, css_killed_ref_fn);
4944}
4945
4946/**
4947 * cgroup_destroy_locked - the first stage of cgroup destruction
4948 * @cgrp: cgroup to be destroyed
4949 *
4950 * css's make use of percpu refcnts whose killing latency shouldn't be
4951 * exposed to userland and are RCU protected. Also, cgroup core needs to
4952 * guarantee that css_tryget_online() won't succeed by the time
4953 * ->css_offline() is invoked. To satisfy all the requirements,
4954 * destruction is implemented in the following two steps.
4955 *
4956 * s1. Verify @cgrp can be destroyed and mark it dying. Remove all
4957 * userland visible parts and start killing the percpu refcnts of
4958 * css's. Set up so that the next stage will be kicked off once all
4959 * the percpu refcnts are confirmed to be killed.
4960 *
4961 * s2. Invoke ->css_offline(), mark the cgroup dead and proceed with the
4962 * rest of destruction. Once all cgroup references are gone, the
4963 * cgroup is RCU-freed.
4964 *
4965 * This function implements s1. After this step, @cgrp is gone as far as
4966 * the userland is concerned and a new cgroup with the same name may be
4967 * created. As cgroup doesn't care about the names internally, this
4968 * doesn't cause any problem.
4969 */
4970static int cgroup_destroy_locked(struct cgroup *cgrp)
4971 __releases(&cgroup_mutex) __acquires(&cgroup_mutex)
4972{
4973 struct cgroup *tcgrp, *parent = cgroup_parent(cgrp);
4974 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
4975 struct cgrp_cset_link *link;
4976 int ssid;
4977
4978 lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4979
4980 /*
4981 * Only migration can raise populated from zero and we're already
4982 * holding cgroup_mutex.
4983 */
4984 if (cgroup_is_populated(cgrp))
4985 return -EBUSY;
4986
4987 /*
4988 * Make sure there's no live children. We can't test emptiness of
4989 * ->self.children as dead children linger on it while being
4990 * drained; otherwise, "rmdir parent/child parent" may fail.
4991 */
4992 if (css_has_online_children(&cgrp->self))
4993 return -EBUSY;
4994
4995 /*
4996 * Mark @cgrp and the associated csets dead. The former prevents
4997 * further task migration and child creation by disabling
4998 * cgroup_lock_live_group(). The latter makes the csets ignored by
4999 * the migration path.
5000 */
5001 cgrp->self.flags &= ~CSS_ONLINE;
5002
5003 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5004 list_for_each_entry(link, &cgrp->cset_links, cset_link)
5005 link->cset->dead = true;
5006 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5007
5008 /* initiate massacre of all css's */
5009 for_each_css(css, ssid, cgrp)
5010 kill_css(css);
5011
5012 /*
5013 * Remove @cgrp directory along with the base files. @cgrp has an
5014 * extra ref on its kn.
5015 */
5016 kernfs_remove(cgrp->kn);
5017
5018 if (parent && cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
5019 parent->nr_threaded_children--;
5020
5021 for (tcgrp = cgroup_parent(cgrp); tcgrp; tcgrp = cgroup_parent(tcgrp)) {
5022 tcgrp->nr_descendants--;
5023 tcgrp->nr_dying_descendants++;
5024 }
5025
5026 cgroup1_check_for_release(parent);
5027
5028 /* put the base reference */
5029 percpu_ref_kill(&cgrp->self.refcnt);
5030
5031 return 0;
5032};
5033
5034int cgroup_rmdir(struct kernfs_node *kn)
5035{
5036 struct cgroup *cgrp;
5037 int ret = 0;
5038
5039 cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(kn, false);
5040 if (!cgrp)
5041 return 0;
5042
5043 ret = cgroup_destroy_locked(cgrp);
5044
5045 if (!ret)
5046 trace_cgroup_rmdir(cgrp);
5047
5048 cgroup_kn_unlock(kn);
5049 return ret;
5050}

5053 .show_options = cgroup_show_options,
5054 .remount_fs = cgroup_remount,

5059
5060static void __init cgroup_init_subsys(struct cgroup_subsys *ss, bool early)
5061{
5062 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
5063
5064 pr_debug("Initializing cgroup subsys %s\n", ss->name);
5065
5066 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
5067
5068 idr_init(&ss->css_idr);
5069 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&ss->cfts);
5070
5071 /* Create the root cgroup state for this subsystem */
5072 ss->root = &cgrp_dfl_root;
5073 css = ss->css_alloc(cgroup_css(&cgrp_dfl_root.cgrp, ss));
5074 /* We don't handle early failures gracefully */
5075 BUG_ON(IS_ERR(css));
5076 init_and_link_css(css, ss, &cgrp_dfl_root.cgrp);
5077
5078 /*
5079 * Root csses are never destroyed and we can't initialize
5080 * percpu_ref during early init. Disable refcnting.
5081 */
5082 css->flags |= CSS_NO_REF;
5083
5084 if (early) {
5085 /* allocation can't be done safely during early init */
5086 css->id = 1;
5087 } else {
5088 css->id = cgroup_idr_alloc(&ss->css_idr, css, 1, 2, GFP_KERNEL);
5089 BUG_ON(css->id < 0);
5090 }
5091
5092 /* Update the init_css_set to contain a subsys
5093 * pointer to this state - since the subsystem is
5094 * newly registered, all tasks and hence the
5095 * init_css_set is in the subsystem's root cgroup. */
5096 init_css_set.subsys[ss->id] = css;
5097
5098 have_fork_callback |= (bool)ss->fork << ss->id;
5099 have_exit_callback |= (bool)ss->exit << ss->id;
5100 have_free_callback |= (bool)ss->free << ss->id;
5101 have_canfork_callback |= (bool)ss->can_fork << ss->id;
5102
5103 /* At system boot, before all subsystems have been
5104 * registered, no tasks have been forked, so we don't
5105 * need to invoke fork callbacks here. */
5106 BUG_ON(!list_empty(&init_task.tasks));
5107
5108 BUG_ON(online_css(css));
5109
5110 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
5111}

5113/**
5114 * cgroup_init_early - cgroup initialization at system boot
5115 *
5116 * Initialize cgroups at system boot, and initialize any
5117 * subsystems that request early init.
5118 */
5119int __init cgroup_init_early(void)
5120{
5121 static struct cgroup_sb_opts __initdata opts;
5122 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5123 int i;
5124
5125 init_cgroup_root(&cgrp_dfl_root, &opts);
5126 cgrp_dfl_root.cgrp.self.flags |= CSS_NO_REF;
5127
5128 RCU_INIT_POINTER(init_task.cgroups, &init_css_set);
5129
5130 for_each_subsys(ss, i) {
5131 WARN(!ss->css_alloc || !ss->css_free || ss->name || ss->id,
5132 "invalid cgroup_subsys %d:%s css_alloc=%p css_free=%p id:name=%d:%s\n",
5133 i, cgroup_subsys_name[i], ss->css_alloc, ss->css_free,
5134 ss->id, ss->name);
5135 WARN(strlen(cgroup_subsys_name[i]) > MAX_CGROUP_TYPE_NAMELEN,
5136 "cgroup_subsys_name %s too long\n", cgroup_subsys_name[i]);
5137
5138 ss->id = i;
5139 ss->name = cgroup_subsys_name[i];
5140 if (!ss->legacy_name)
5141 ss->legacy_name = cgroup_subsys_name[i];
5142
5143 if (ss->early_init)
5144 cgroup_init_subsys(ss, true);
5145 }
5146 return 0;
5147}
5148
5149static u16 cgroup_disable_mask __initdata;
5150
5151/**
5152 * cgroup_init - cgroup initialization
5153 *
5154 * Register cgroup filesystem and /proc file, and initialize
5155 * any subsystems that didn't request early init.
5156 */
5157int __init cgroup_init(void)
5158{
5159 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5160 int ssid;
5161
5162 BUILD_BUG_ON(CGROUP_SUBSYS_COUNT > 16);
5163 BUG_ON(percpu_init_rwsem(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem));
5164 BUG_ON(cgroup_init_cftypes(NULL, cgroup_base_files));
5165 BUG_ON(cgroup_init_cftypes(NULL, cgroup1_base_files));
5166
5167 /*
5168 * The latency of the synchronize_sched() is too high for cgroups,
5169 * avoid it at the cost of forcing all readers into the slow path.
5170 */
5171 rcu_sync_enter_start(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem.rss);
5172
5173 get_user_ns(init_cgroup_ns.user_ns);
5174
5175 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
5176
5177 /*
5178 * Add init_css_set to the hash table so that dfl_root can link to
5179 * it during init.
5180 */
5181 hash_add(css_set_table, &init_css_set.hlist,
5182 css_set_hash(init_css_set.subsys));
5183
5184 BUG_ON(cgroup_setup_root(&cgrp_dfl_root, 0, 0));
5185
5186 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
5187
5188 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
5189 if (ss->early_init) {
5190 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
5191 init_css_set.subsys[ss->id];
5192
5193 css->id = cgroup_idr_alloc(&ss->css_idr, css, 1, 2,
5194 GFP_KERNEL);
5195 BUG_ON(css->id < 0);
5196 } else {
5197 cgroup_init_subsys(ss, false);
5198 }
5199
5200 list_add_tail(&init_css_set.e_cset_node[ssid],
5201 &cgrp_dfl_root.cgrp.e_csets[ssid]);
5202
5203 /*
5204 * Setting dfl_root subsys_mask needs to consider the
5205 * disabled flag and cftype registration needs kmalloc,
5206 * both of which aren't available during early_init.
5207 */
5208 if (cgroup_disable_mask & (1 << ssid)) {
5209 static_branch_disable(cgroup_subsys_enabled_key[ssid]);
5210 printk(KERN_INFO "Disabling %s control group subsystem\n",
5211 ss->name);
5212 continue;
5213 }
5214
5215 if (cgroup1_ssid_disabled(ssid))
5216 printk(KERN_INFO "Disabling %s control group subsystem in v1 mounts\n",
5217 ss->name);
5218
5219 cgrp_dfl_root.subsys_mask |= 1 << ss->id;
5220
5221 /* implicit controllers must be threaded too */
5222 WARN_ON(ss->implicit_on_dfl && !ss->threaded);
5223
5224 if (ss->implicit_on_dfl)
5225 cgrp_dfl_implicit_ss_mask |= 1 << ss->id;
5226 else if (!ss->dfl_cftypes)
5227 cgrp_dfl_inhibit_ss_mask |= 1 << ss->id;
5228
5229 if (ss->threaded)
5230 cgrp_dfl_threaded_ss_mask |= 1 << ss->id;
5231
5232 if (ss->dfl_cftypes == ss->legacy_cftypes) {
5233 WARN_ON(cgroup_add_cftypes(ss, ss->dfl_cftypes));
5234 } else {
5235 WARN_ON(cgroup_add_dfl_cftypes(ss, ss->dfl_cftypes));
5236 WARN_ON(cgroup_add_legacy_cftypes(ss, ss->legacy_cftypes));
5237 }
5238
5239 if (ss->bind)
5240 ss->bind(init_css_set.subsys[ssid]);
5241
5242 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
5243 css_populate_dir(init_css_set.subsys[ssid]);
5244 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
5245 }
5246
5247 /* init_css_set.subsys[] has been updated, re-hash */
5248 hash_del(&init_css_set.hlist);
5249 hash_add(css_set_table, &init_css_set.hlist,
5250 css_set_hash(init_css_set.subsys));
5251
5252 WARN_ON(sysfs_create_mount_point(fs_kobj, "cgroup"));
5253 WARN_ON(register_filesystem(&cgroup_fs_type));

5288/*
5289 * proc_cgroup_show()
5290 * - Print task's cgroup paths into seq_file, one line for each hierarchy
5291 * - Used for /proc/<pid>/cgroup.
5292 */
5293int proc_cgroup_show(struct seq_file *m, struct pid_namespace *ns,
5294 struct pid *pid, struct task_struct *tsk)
5295{
5296 char *buf;
5297 int retval;
5298 struct cgroup_root *root;
5299
5300 retval = -ENOMEM;
5301 buf = kmalloc(PATH_MAX, GFP_KERNEL);
5302 if (!buf)
5303 goto out;
5304
5305 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
5306 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5307
5308 for_each_root(root) {
5309 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5310 struct cgroup *cgrp;
5311 int ssid, count = 0;
5312
5313 if (root == &cgrp_dfl_root && !cgrp_dfl_visible)
5314 continue;
5315
5316 seq_printf(m, "%d:", root->hierarchy_id);
5317 if (root != &cgrp_dfl_root)
5318 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid)
5319 if (root->subsys_mask & (1 << ssid))
5320 seq_printf(m, "%s%s", count++ ? "," : "",
5321 ss->legacy_name);
5322 if (strlen(root->name))
5323 seq_printf(m, "%sname=%s", count ? "," : "",
5324 root->name);
5325 seq_putc(m, ':');
5326
5327 cgrp = task_cgroup_from_root(tsk, root);
5328
5329 /*
5330 * On traditional hierarchies, all zombie tasks show up as
5331 * belonging to the root cgroup. On the default hierarchy,
5332 * while a zombie doesn't show up in "cgroup.procs" and
5333 * thus can't be migrated, its /proc/PID/cgroup keeps
5334 * reporting the cgroup it belonged to before exiting. If
5335 * the cgroup is removed before the zombie is reaped,
5336 * " (deleted)" is appended to the cgroup path.
5337 */
5338 if (cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp) || !(tsk->flags & PF_EXITING)) {
5339 retval = cgroup_path_ns_locked(cgrp, buf, PATH_MAX,
5340 current->nsproxy->cgroup_ns);
5341 if (retval >= PATH_MAX)
5342 retval = -ENAMETOOLONG;
5343 if (retval < 0)
5344 goto out_unlock;
5345
5346 seq_puts(m, buf);
5347 } else {
5348 seq_puts(m, "/");
5349 }
5350
5351 if (cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp) && cgroup_is_dead(cgrp))
5352 seq_puts(m, " (deleted)\n");
5353 else
5354 seq_putc(m, '\n');
5355 }
5356
5357 retval = 0;
5358out_unlock:
5359 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5360 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
5361 kfree(buf);
5362out:
5363 return retval;
5364}

5366/**
5367 * cgroup_fork - initialize cgroup related fields during copy_process()
5368 * @child: pointer to task_struct of forking parent process.
5369 *
5370 * A task is associated with the init_css_set until cgroup_post_fork()
5371 * attaches it to the parent's css_set. Empty cg_list indicates that
5372 * @child isn't holding reference to its css_set.
5373 */
5374void cgroup_fork(struct task_struct *child)
5375{
5376 RCU_INIT_POINTER(child->cgroups, &init_css_set);
5377 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&child->cg_list);
5378}

5380/**
5381 * cgroup_can_fork - called on a new task before the process is exposed
5382 * @child: the task in question.
5383 *
5384 * This calls the subsystem can_fork() callbacks. If the can_fork() callback
5385 * returns an error, the fork aborts with that error code. This allows for
5386 * a cgroup subsystem to conditionally allow or deny new forks.
5387 */
5388int cgroup_can_fork(struct task_struct *child)
5389{
5390 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5391 int i, j, ret;
5392
5393 do_each_subsys_mask(ss, i, have_canfork_callback) {
5394 ret = ss->can_fork(child);
5395 if (ret)
5396 goto out_revert;
5397 } while_each_subsys_mask();
5398
5399 return 0;
5400
5401out_revert:
5402 for_each_subsys(ss, j) {
5403 if (j >= i)
5404 break;
5405 if (ss->cancel_fork)
5406 ss->cancel_fork(child);
5407 }
5408
5409 return ret;
5410}
5411
5412/**
5413 * cgroup_cancel_fork - called if a fork failed after cgroup_can_fork()
5414 * @child: the task in question
5415 *
5416 * This calls the cancel_fork() callbacks if a fork failed *after*
5417 * cgroup_can_fork() succeded.
5418 */
5419void cgroup_cancel_fork(struct task_struct *child)
5420{
5421 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5422 int i;
5423
5424 for_each_subsys(ss, i)
5425 if (ss->cancel_fork)
5426 ss->cancel_fork(child);
5427}
5428
5429/**
5430 * cgroup_post_fork - called on a new task after adding it to the task list
5431 * @child: the task in question
5432 *
5433 * Adds the task to the list running through its css_set if necessary and
5434 * call the subsystem fork() callbacks. Has to be after the task is
5435 * visible on the task list in case we race with the first call to
5436 * cgroup_task_iter_start() - to guarantee that the new task ends up on its
5437 * list.
5438 */
5439void cgroup_post_fork(struct task_struct *child)
5440{
5441 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5442 int i;
5443
5444 /*
5445 * This may race against cgroup_enable_task_cg_lists(). As that
5446 * function sets use_task_css_set_links before grabbing
5447 * tasklist_lock and we just went through tasklist_lock to add
5448 * @child, it's guaranteed that either we see the set
5449 * use_task_css_set_links or cgroup_enable_task_cg_lists() sees
5450 * @child during its iteration.
5451 *
5452 * If we won the race, @child is associated with %current's
5453 * css_set. Grabbing css_set_lock guarantees both that the
5454 * association is stable, and, on completion of the parent's
5455 * migration, @child is visible in the source of migration or
5456 * already in the destination cgroup. This guarantee is necessary
5457 * when implementing operations which need to migrate all tasks of
5458 * a cgroup to another.
5459 *
5460 * Note that if we lose to cgroup_enable_task_cg_lists(), @child
5461 * will remain in init_css_set. This is safe because all tasks are
5462 * in the init_css_set before cg_links is enabled and there's no
5463 * operation which transfers all tasks out of init_css_set.
5464 */
5465 if (use_task_css_set_links) {
5466 struct css_set *cset;
5467
5468 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5469 cset = task_css_set(current);
5470 if (list_empty(&child->cg_list)) {
5471 get_css_set(cset);
5472 cset->nr_tasks++;
5473 css_set_move_task(child, NULL, cset, false);
5474 }
5475 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5476 }
5477
5478 /*
5479 * Call ss->fork(). This must happen after @child is linked on
5480 * css_set; otherwise, @child might change state between ->fork()
5481 * and addition to css_set.
5482 */
5483 do_each_subsys_mask(ss, i, have_fork_callback) {
5484 ss->fork(child);
5485 } while_each_subsys_mask();
5486}
5487
5488/**
5489 * cgroup_exit - detach cgroup from exiting task
5490 * @tsk: pointer to task_struct of exiting process
5491 *
5492 * Description: Detach cgroup from @tsk and release it.
5493 *
5494 * Note that cgroups marked notify_on_release force every task in
5495 * them to take the global cgroup_mutex mutex when exiting.
5496 * This could impact scaling on very large systems. Be reluctant to
5497 * use notify_on_release cgroups where very high task exit scaling
5498 * is required on large systems.
5499 *
5500 * We set the exiting tasks cgroup to the root cgroup (top_cgroup). We
5501 * call cgroup_exit() while the task is still competent to handle
5502 * notify_on_release(), then leave the task attached to the root cgroup in
5503 * each hierarchy for the remainder of its exit. No need to bother with
5504 * init_css_set refcnting. init_css_set never goes away and we can't race
5505 * with migration path - PF_EXITING is visible to migration path.
5506 */
5507void cgroup_exit(struct task_struct *tsk)
5508{
5509 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5510 struct css_set *cset;
5511 int i;
5512
5513 /*
5514 * Unlink from @tsk from its css_set. As migration path can't race
5515 * with us, we can check css_set and cg_list without synchronization.
5516 */
5517 cset = task_css_set(tsk);
5518
5519 if (!list_empty(&tsk->cg_list)) {
5520 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5521 css_set_move_task(tsk, cset, NULL, false);
5522 cset->nr_tasks--;
5523 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5524 } else {
5525 get_css_set(cset);
5526 }
5527
5528 /* see cgroup_post_fork() for details */
5529 do_each_subsys_mask(ss, i, have_exit_callback) {
5530 ss->exit(tsk);
5531 } while_each_subsys_mask();
5532}
5533
5534void cgroup_free(struct task_struct *task)
5535{
5536 struct css_set *cset = task_css_set(task);
5537 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5538 int ssid;
5539
5540 do_each_subsys_mask(ss, ssid, have_free_callback) {
5541 ss->free(task);
5542 } while_each_subsys_mask();
5543
5544 put_css_set(cset);
5545}

5547static int __init cgroup_disable(char *str)
5548{
5549 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
5550 char *token;
5551 int i;
5552
5553 while ((token = strsep(&str, ",")) != NULL) {
5554 if (!*token)
5555 continue;
5556
5557 for_each_subsys(ss, i) {
5558 if (strcmp(token, ss->name) &&
5559 strcmp(token, ss->legacy_name))
5560 continue;
5561 cgroup_disable_mask |= 1 << i;
5562 }
5563 }
5564 return 1;
5565}

5568/**
5569 * css_tryget_online_from_dir - get corresponding css from a cgroup dentry
5570 * @dentry: directory dentry of interest
5571 * @ss: subsystem of interest
5572 *
5573 * If @dentry is a directory for a cgroup which has @ss enabled on it, try
5574 * to get the corresponding css and return it. If such css doesn't exist
5575 * or can't be pinned, an ERR_PTR value is returned.
5576 */
5577struct cgroup_subsys_state *css_tryget_online_from_dir(struct dentry *dentry,
5578 struct cgroup_subsys *ss)
5579{
5580 struct kernfs_node *kn = kernfs_node_from_dentry(dentry);
5581 struct file_system_type *s_type = dentry->d_sb->s_type;
5582 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css = NULL;
5583 struct cgroup *cgrp;
5584
5585 /* is @dentry a cgroup dir? */
5586 if ((s_type != &cgroup_fs_type && s_type != &cgroup2_fs_type) ||
5587 !kn || kernfs_type(kn) != KERNFS_DIR)
5588 return ERR_PTR(-EBADF);
5589
5590 rcu_read_lock();
5591
5592 /*
5593 * This path doesn't originate from kernfs and @kn could already
5594 * have been or be removed at any point. @kn->priv is RCU
5595 * protected for this access. See css_release_work_fn() for details.
5596 */
5597 cgrp = rcu_dereference(*(void __rcu __force **)&kn->priv);
5598 if (cgrp)
5599 css = cgroup_css(cgrp, ss);
5600
5601 if (!css || !css_tryget_online(css))
5602 css = ERR_PTR(-ENOENT);
5603
5604 rcu_read_unlock();
5605 return css;
5606}

5622/**
5623 * cgroup_get_from_path - lookup and get a cgroup from its default hierarchy path
5624 * @path: path on the default hierarchy
5625 *
5626 * Find the cgroup at @path on the default hierarchy, increment its
5627 * reference count and return it. Returns pointer to the found cgroup on
5628 * success, ERR_PTR(-ENOENT) if @path doens't exist and ERR_PTR(-ENOTDIR)
5629 * if @path points to a non-directory.
5630 */
5631struct cgroup *cgroup_get_from_path(const char *path)
5632{
5633 struct kernfs_node *kn;
5634 struct cgroup *cgrp;
5635
5636 mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
5637
5638 kn = kernfs_walk_and_get(cgrp_dfl_root.cgrp.kn, path);
5639 if (kn) {
5640 if (kernfs_type(kn) == KERNFS_DIR) {
5641 cgrp = kn->priv;
5642 cgroup_get_live(cgrp);
5643 } else {
5644 cgrp = ERR_PTR(-ENOTDIR);
5645 }
5646 kernfs_put(kn);
5647 } else {
5648 cgrp = ERR_PTR(-ENOENT);
5649 }
5650
5651 mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
5652 return cgrp;
5653}
5654EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(cgroup_get_from_path);

5656/**
5657 * cgroup_get_from_fd - get a cgroup pointer from a fd
5658 * @fd: fd obtained by open(cgroup2_dir)
5659 *
5660 * Find the cgroup from a fd which should be obtained
5661 * by opening a cgroup directory. Returns a pointer to the
5662 * cgroup on success. ERR_PTR is returned if the cgroup
5663 * cannot be found.
5664 */
5665struct cgroup *cgroup_get_from_fd(int fd)
5666{
5667 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
5668 struct cgroup *cgrp;
5669 struct file *f;
5670
5671 f = fget_raw(fd);
5672 if (!f)
5673 return ERR_PTR(-EBADF);
5674
5675 css = css_tryget_online_from_dir(f->f_path.dentry, NULL);
5676 fput(f);
5677 if (IS_ERR(css))
5678 return ERR_CAST(css);
5679
5680 cgrp = css->cgroup;
5681 if (!cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp)) {
5682 cgroup_put(cgrp);
5683 return ERR_PTR(-EBADF);
5684 }
5685
5686 return cgrp;
5687}
5688EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(cgroup_get_from_fd);

5706 cgroup_sk_alloc_disabled = true;

5714
5715void cgroup_sk_alloc(struct sock_cgroup_data *skcd)
5716{
5717 if (cgroup_sk_alloc_disabled)
5718 return;
5719
5720 /* Socket clone path */
5721 if (skcd->val) {
5722 /*
5723 * We might be cloning a socket which is left in an empty
5724 * cgroup and the cgroup might have already been rmdir'd.
5725 * Don't use cgroup_get_live().
5726 */
5727 cgroup_get(sock_cgroup_ptr(skcd));
5728 return;
5729 }
5730
5731 rcu_read_lock();
5732
5733 while (true) {
5734 struct css_set *cset;
5735
5736 cset = task_css_set(current);
5737 if (likely(cgroup_tryget(cset->dfl_cgrp))) {
5738 skcd->val = (unsigned long)cset->dfl_cgrp;
5739 break;
5740 }
5741 cpu_relax();
5742 }
5743
5744 rcu_read_unlock();
5745}

5748{

5750}
